                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d551">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">837.51/1540: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Cuba</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Guggenheim</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Habana</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-01-16T11:00:00-05:00"
                            >January 16, 1933—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 12:25 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>6. My telegram No. 4, January 12, 4 p.m. On January 13th message was informally
                    conveyed to the Embassy by Secretary of the Treasury that Cuban Government had
                    no present intention of issuing Treasury certificates and that consideration of
                    the matter would remain in abeyance until budget has been balanced. A similar
                    statement appeared in the newspapers. This morning I received a letter dated
                    January 13th from the President in reply to mine of January 11th, in which he
                    states that his Government has not determined to issue bonds, certificates of
                    indebtedness or other obligations for any purpose nor has it taken any steps in
                    connection therewith.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Guggenheim</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
